SIMPLE: snood
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Snood
<hw>Snood</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>sn⟦omac⟧d</ets>. Cf. <ets>Snare</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
fillet which binds the hair of a young unmarried woman, and is
emblematic of her maiden character.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And seldom was a <qex>snood</qex> amid⟦br⟧
Such wild, luxuriant ringlets hid.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A short line (often of horsehair) connecting a
fishing line with the hook; a snell; a leader.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snood</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Snood
<hw>Snood</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To bind or braid up, as the hair,
with a snood.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snooded</ent>⟦br⟧
